<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ871103-0156 </DOCNO><HL> Acme-Cleveland ChairmanTo Join Investment Firm</HL><DD> 11/03/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> AMT WNEWS </IN><DATELINE> CLEVELAND  </DATELINE><TEXT>   B. Charles Ames, chairman of Acme-Cleveland Corp., said he is leaving the company to join Clayton andamp; Dubilier, a New York private investment firm, as a partner.    Mr. Ames, 62 years old, said he will relinquish his post at Acme-Cleveland, a maker of telecommunications products and sensor devices, either at the next board meeting late this month or at the annual shareholders meeting in January.    On April 1, Mr. Ames relinquished his title as chief executive officer to David L. Swift, 51, who had been vice president-administration. Mr. Swift also was named Acme's president then.    Before joining Acme-Cleveland in 1981, Mr. Ames had been president and chief executive officer of Reliance Electric Co., which was sold to Exxon Corp. in 1979. He has co-authored two management books. Clayton andamp; Dubilier specializes in management buy-outs. </TEXT></DOC>